            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>What is on-base percentage (OBP)?</h2>
              <p>
                On-base percentage (OBP) is a core baseball and softball
                statistic that measures how often a hitter reaches base safely
                without making an out. Unlike batting average, OBP rewards
                players for
                <strong>walks</strong> and <strong>hit-by-pitch</strong>, not
                just hits.
              </p>
              <p>
                Because outs are the most valuable &ldquo;currency&rdquo; in
                baseball, OBP is one of the best single-number indicators of a
                player&rsquo;s offensive value. Modern analytics (like
                sabermetrics and wOBA) heavily emphasize getting on base over
                traditional batting average.
              </p>

              <h2>Official OBP formula</h2>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Standard (official) OBP formula:
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{OBP} = \frac{H + BB + HBP}{AB + BB + HBP + SF} \]
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li><strong>H</strong> = Hits</li>
                  <li><strong>BB</strong> = Walks (bases on balls)</li>
                  <li><strong>HBP</strong> = Hit by pitch</li>
                  <li><strong>AB</strong> = At-bats</li>
                  <li><strong>SF</strong> = Sacrifice flies</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">
                  Sacrifice bunts (<strong>SH</strong>) are
                  <em>not</em> included in the OBP denominator. Reaching on
                  error (<strong>ROE</strong>) is also excluded in the official
                  formula.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Extended OBP including errors</h3>
              <p>
                Some coaches and analysts like to track how often a player ends
                up on base in practice, regardless of whether it was scored as a
                hit or an error. In that case, they use an
                <strong>extended OBP</strong>:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Extended OBP (non-official):</p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{OBP}_{\text{ext}} = \frac{H + BB + HBP + ROE}{AB + BB
                  + HBP + SF} \]
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">
                  Our calculator supports both versions. Use the mode toggle to
                  include or exclude <strong>ROE</strong> (reached on error).
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Step-by-step: how to calculate OBP</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Collect the stats</strong> for the period you care
                  about (game, series, season, career):
                  <ul>
                    <li>Hits (H)</li>
                    <li>Walks (BB)</li>
                    <li>Hit by pitch (HBP)</li>
                    <li>At-bats (AB)</li>
                    <li>Sacrifice flies (SF)</li>
                    <li>
                      Optionally: Reached on error (ROE) if you want extended
                      OBP
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Compute times on base</strong> (standard):
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    \[ \text{Times on base} = H + BB + HBP \]
                  </div>
                  <p>If you&rsquo;re using extended OBP, add ROE as well:</p>
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    \[ \text{Times on base}_{\text{ext}} = H + BB + HBP + ROE \]
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Compute the OBP denominator</strong>:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    \[ \text{Denominator} = AB + BB + HBP + SF \]
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Divide and round</strong>:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    \[ \text{OBP} = \frac{\text{Times on
                    base}}{\text{Denominator}} \]
                  </div>
                  <p>
                    Round to three decimal places, like <code>.345</code>. In
                    box scores, the leading zero is usually omitted.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>Suppose a player has the following line:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>H = 2 hits</li>
                <li>BB = 1 walk</li>
                <li>HBP = 0</li>
                <li>AB = 4 at-bats</li>
                <li>SF = 0 sacrifice flies</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Then:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>Times on base = 2 + 1 + 0 = 3</p>
                <p>Denominator = 4 + 1 + 0 + 0 = 5</p>
                <p>\[ \text{OBP} = \frac{3}{5} = 0.600 \]</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                This player reached base 60% of the time in those plate
                appearances, which is an outstanding OBP in any realistic
                sample.
              </p>

              <h2>What is a good OBP?</h2>
              <p>
                Context matters (league, era, ballpark), but for modern MLB a
                rough rule of thumb is:
              </p>
              <table class="min-w-full text-sm border border-gray-200">
                <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                  <tr>
                    <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left border-b">OBP</th>
                    <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left border-b">Quality</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="px-3 py-1 border-b">&lt; .300</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-1 border-b">Poor</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="px-3 py-1 border-b">.300 – .320</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-1 border-b">Below average</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="px-3 py-1 border-b">.320 – .340</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-1 border-b">Around league average</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="px-3 py-1 border-b">.340 – .370</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-1 border-b">Good</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="px-3 py-1 border-b">.370 – .400</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-1 border-b">Excellent</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="px-3 py-1">&gt; .400</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-1">Elite / MVP-level</td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
              <p>
                In youth leagues and recreational softball, OBP values can be
                higher because of more walks, errors, and weaker defense. Use
                league averages as your benchmark when possible.
              </p>

              <h2>OBP vs. batting average vs. OPS</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Batting average (AVG)</strong>: \[ \text{AVG} =
                  \frac{H}{AB} \] Counts only hits, ignores walks and HBP.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>On-base percentage (OBP)</strong>: \[ \text{OBP} =
                  \frac{H + BB + HBP}{AB + BB + HBP + SF} \] Measures how often
                  a player avoids making an out.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Slugging percentage (SLG)</strong>: \[ \text{SLG} =
                  \frac{\text{Total bases}}{AB} \] Measures power (extra-base
                  hits).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                A common combined metric is <strong>OPS</strong> (On-base Plus
                Slugging): <code>OPS = OBP + SLG</code>. Many analysts still
                consider OBP the more important half of OPS because getting on
                base is the foundation of scoring runs.
              </p>

              <h2>Common questions about OBP</h2>
              <h3>Why are sacrifice flies in the denominator?</h3>
              <p>
                Sacrifice flies (<strong>SF</strong>) are counted in the OBP
                denominator because they are plate appearances where the batter
                makes an out but still contributes offensively (a run scores).
                Excluding them would slightly inflate OBP for players who hit
                many sac flies.
              </p>

              <h3>Why aren&rsquo;t sacrifice bunts included?</h3>
              <p>
                Sacrifice bunts (<strong>SH</strong>) are generally considered a
                strategic decision by the manager rather than a measure of the
                batter&rsquo;s ability to reach base. For that reason, they are
                excluded from the OBP denominator.
              </p>

              <h3>Why doesn&rsquo;t OBP include errors?</h3>
              <p>
                Official scoring treats reaching on error as a defensive
                mistake, not an offensive success. To keep stats comparable
                across eras and scoring practices, the official OBP formula
                excludes
                <strong>ROE</strong>. However, from a team strategy perspective,
                a batter who frequently puts the ball in play hard enough to
                force errors can still be very valuable, which is why some
                coaches track extended OBP including ROE.
              </p>

              <h3>Can OBP be exactly 1.000 or 0.000?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes, in small samples. If a player reaches base in every
                qualifying plate appearance (e.g., 3 walks in 3 PA), OBP =
                1.000. If they never reach base (e.g., 0-for-10 with no walks or
